properties.country_bio: Utah is known for its outdoor recreation. With its dramatic landscape and contrasting weather on either sides of the state, you can experience skiing in the snowy Park City and hike in the hidden trails of the Arches National Park in the same month.

Stretching over 30000 acres, Bonneville Salt Flats is barren as far as your eyes can see. The landscapes here were formed during the ice age and continue to evolve on a daily basis. The entire vicinity looks like a snowfilled plain with mountain peaks breaking the view once in a while.

Probably the most beautiful place on Earth, Sedona nestles gently in a geological wonderland and is every wanderer's dream. Situated in the middle of the magnificent Arizona desert, Sedona hosts breathtaking landscapes, hiking opportunities, calm lakes and more!

Subway at Zion is a narrow strip in the Zion National Park in Utah which takes you to an alienated part of the universe. This beautiful stretch of natural phenomenon feature an emerald lake, rocky shelter towering above and the silence of nature tingling all your senses strong.

Probably one of the most diverse countries in the world. Every state in the US is like it's own country, the bustling metropolis of New York, the rugged landscape of Arizona, the wonderworld of Disneyland - all provide different experiences. It takes a lifetime to explore and indulge in the culture of this humongous country.

The Death Valley is one of the most underrated national parks in all of US. It's not brimming with luscious trees nor does it have emerald lakes everywhere, but it is surely interesting. It houses the Badwater Basin which is the lowest and hottest point in North America and is made up of salt flats that form unique shapes as far as your eyes can see.

Enter a different dimension with your visit to the first national park in the world. The Yellowstone features some of the most exaggerated natural wonders in the world. Colourful geysers plonked in between a grove of tall trees is just one of the most spectacular things you can witness here.

The coast of Maine hosts some of the most iconic views ever. With rocky shores housing tall lighthouses, this coast is a dream come true. With an endless array of sightseeing opportunities along with adventure sports, these national parks have offer something for everyone.

The state of Vermont is known for its hiking expeditions. Witness a massive green area in the the Green Mountains and follow paved hiking trails for a  breathtaking sunset view along with formations of colonies of multicoloured trees and a stream flowing in the valley topping it all.

The finger lakes is a group of eleven narrow lakes in New York. This region features beautiful waterfalls, lakes amidst a grove, barbecue and camping opportunities, and more! From hiking and biking, to boating and fishing, you can either choose to relax or get your adventure spirits up here.

Being North America's biggest population of wild bison, the Wood Buffalo National Park is definitely worth a visit. This whole region encompasses an enormous area of undistrubed grassland and sedge meadows in the continent. With neverending roads to streams flowing through the valley, this park features amazing views, scenic beauty and hiking opportunities.

With influences of the Aztec to the colonies built up by the Spanish, Mexico is a unique country woven by both cultures. From the hidden caves of Tulum to the ancient monument of Cancun, Mexico is staggering with travel opportunities for all. And of course, soaking in the sun with margaritas and tacos in the Playa del Carmen beach is a given.

Home to volcanic beaches, tapered mountains and tropical forests, St Lucia is a dream. This destination is not meant only for a romantic getaway but also some of the most adventurous experiences like volcano diving and the island of the iguanas.
